applicationInfo.name: dz-external-workflow-integration
applicationInfo.description:
**Important**: This prototype is **not** a production grade system, and this threat model is not comprehensive or complete. This document does not list all possible threats, and where threats do have mapped mitigations - these mitigations are note deemed to be complete.

Consider this as a starting point for your own diligence and threat modeling as part of your path-to-production.

dataflow.description: **Note:** A data flow diagram has not been captured at this stage. You should consider creating a data-flow diagram as part of your path to production.

assumptions.content: Only authorized and trusted users have access to Jira tickets
Jira credentials allows only ticket creation and status check (no admin)
Least privileged access to the account

mitigations.content: Use Client Certificate for Jira authentication
Lambda function only relies on issue id and not issue's content

metadata.value: Implement secure communication channels and encryption techniques (e.g., TLS/SSL) to protect the data in transit between the AWS services and the Atlassian Jira Service Management API Endpoint. This can help mitigate the risk of man-in-the-middle attacks and interception of sensitive data.

threats.statement: An internal actor who has permissions to change Jira ticket content can manipulate the ticket content, which leads to to incorrect or malicious issue details, resulting in reduced integrity of approval process
threats.prerequisites: who has permissions to change Jira ticket content
threats.threatImpact: to incorrect or malicious issue details

threats.statement: An internal actor who has access to Jira credential can operate in Jira and approve subscription requests, which leads to unauthorized approvals, resulting in reduced confidentiality and/or integrity of producer data and access grants
threats.prerequisites: who has access to Jira credential
threats.threatAction: operate in Jira and approve subscription requests

threats.prerequisites: with the ability to manipulate DNS records
threats.threatAction: redirect Jira API calls to a malicious endpoint
threats.statement: A threat actor with the ability to manipulate DNS records can redirect Jira API calls to a malicious endpoint, which leads to exfiltration of sensitive approval data, resulting in reduced confidentiality and/or integrity of producer data and access grants

threats.prerequisites: who can intercept network traffic between AWS Lambda and Jira API
threats.statement: An external threat actor who can intercept network traffic between AWS Lambda and Jira API can manipulate Jira ticket content, which leads to unauthorized approvals, resulting in reduced integrity and/or confidentiality of subscription data

threats.prerequisites: who can intercept network traffic between AWS Lambda and Jira API
threats.threatImpact: unauthorized access to sensitive issue data
threats.statement: An external threat actor who can intercept network traffic between AWS Lambda and Jira API can gain access to sensitive information, which leads to unauthorized access to sensitive issue data, resulting in reduced confidentiality of subscription data

threats.prerequisites: with access to AWS Secrets Manager
threats.threatImpact: unauthorized interactions with the Jira system
threats.statement: An internal actor with access to AWS Secrets Manager can retrieve the Jira API credentials, which leads to unauthorized interactions with the Jira system, resulting in reduced integrity of approval process

threats.threatAction: leverage vulnerabilities in the dependencies we use for our Lambda function code
threats.threatImpact: the threat actor running arbitrary code within the Lambda function
threats.statement: A threat actor can leverage vulnerabilities in the dependencies we use for our Lambda function code, which leads to the threat actor running arbitrary code within the Lambda function, resulting in reduced integrity and/or confidentiality of assets within the trust boundary

threats.prerequisites: who can manipulate the AWS Lambda function responsible for polling Jira status
threats.threatImpact: unauthorized data access grants in Amazon DataZone
threats.statement: A threat actor who can manipulate the AWS Lambda function responsible for polling Jira status can forge approval statuses, which leads to unauthorized data access grants in Amazon DataZone, resulting in reduced confidentiality of producer data
